1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,295
light.

2
00:00:02,315 --> 00:00:10,451
Namotasa bhagavato harahato samma sambodasa.

3
00:00:11,474 --> 00:00:20,772
Namotasa bhagavato harahato samma sambodasa.

4
00:00:20,905 --> 00:00:35,189
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sammasambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

5
00:00:41,359 --> 00:00:44,365
So, we've...

6
00:00:46,082 --> 00:00:56,679
either refreshed our understanding or been introduced to a particular practice, a particular methodology to investigate our situation.

7
00:00:59,505 --> 00:01:00,546
That's the vipassana.

8
00:01:01,829 --> 00:01:12,546
We've gone into the characteristics which is what it is we're trying to actually see more clearly

9
00:01:14,314 --> 00:01:18,661
From the Buddha's point of view, remember, it's the way we're looking which is our fault.

10
00:01:19,421 --> 00:01:23,186
We're not seeing things, as he would put it, as they really are.

11
00:01:24,549 --> 00:01:44,034
And he points to these three avenues of investigation, the impermanence, the idea of not-self, not-me, not-mine, and the psychology around desire, sensual desire, desire which basically says we're seeking happiness in the sensual world.

12
00:01:44,436 --> 00:01:58,159
as the three avenues of investigation which should eventually correct our view and have an effect on us.

13
00:02:02,459 --> 00:02:07,370
In the Eightfold Path, the effect is meant to be systemic, and we'll come to that this evening.

14
00:02:08,352 --> 00:02:14,544
And then we talked about the various hindrances, the mental states that arise in meditation, which we...

15
00:02:15,469 --> 00:02:44,379
have to work with but from the importance of this suffering business it was also recognizing that even though we're investigating these three characteristics the actual process of purifying the heart what would these days be called therapy is actually happening quite unwittingly it's just happening of itself and the main technique there you might say was to depersonalize it

16
00:02:44,917 --> 00:02:53,769
And we depersonalize these emotions when we take the stories away, the stories that turn them into a continuous sense of me or mine.

17
00:02:54,711 --> 00:03:10,552
When we just bury our attention into just the feeling, just the feeling sense of an emotion, the sense, the sensational sense of an emotion, then it becomes a very different sort of experience.

18
00:03:12,135 --> 00:03:18,305
And at that point we have to be aware of our reaction to these things, where another story starts up.

19
00:03:18,465 --> 00:03:20,769
You know, I can't take it, I want this.

20
00:03:21,509 --> 00:03:23,211
The I always appears somewhere.

21
00:03:25,455 --> 00:03:34,228
So now, this evening, it's really the time to talk on the more positive side of how we bring about a transformation.

22
00:03:35,473 --> 00:03:45,534
If we stay just there, you know, there might be an understanding, well, you just end up, you know, without greed or without hatred.

23
00:03:45,682 --> 00:03:54,576
and it's a sort of flat state, or a nondescript state of not being anything.

24
00:03:54,597 --> 00:04:07,917
But according, again, to the Buddha's understanding, what happens is almost a natural transformation of those particular attitudes into their opposites.

25
00:04:07,937 --> 00:04:13,985
In the Zen tradition, they'll tell you that compassion arises naturally with wisdom, see?

26
00:04:14,877 --> 00:04:25,112
And there was one teacher in London, she died recently, her name's just slipped my mind, who wouldn't do any loving-kindness practice, it was a waste of time.

27
00:04:26,875 --> 00:04:31,721
Because from her point of view, with wisdom, compassion arises naturally.

28
00:04:31,971 --> 00:05:00,307
and in a sense that's what you might say happened to the Buddha himself because his great intention was to seek some sort of answer to his own problems even at that most sort of existential level the angst of the question of why am I here in the first place and who am I in the context of the cosmos and all that and having answered all those questions

29
00:05:00,658 --> 00:05:11,259
And understanding what he'd come to realize, like quite naturally, you know, the desire to pass on this information to other human beings just arose naturally.

30
00:05:12,387 --> 00:05:18,696
There was a doubt, a doubt arose in his mind at the time as to whether anybody would actually understand it.

31
00:05:18,776 --> 00:05:21,300
So subtle had been his experience.

32
00:05:22,141 --> 00:05:29,572
And as it's put in the mythology, the great Brahma Sahampati came down and said to him that there were people with only a little dust in their eyes.

33
00:05:29,593 --> 00:05:33,158
So that's when he started off on his teaching journey.

34
00:05:35,882 --> 00:05:37,264
So...

35
00:05:39,100 --> 00:05:51,050
How are we already generating in our practice, in the actual sitting, and with the work we've been doing this weekend, the foundations for this transformation?

36
00:05:51,773 --> 00:06:01,213
So when we talk about transformation, we're just talking about this energy that we experience within ourselves that we call emotions and mental thoughts.

37
00:06:01,675 --> 00:06:11,536
How do we move them over to the opposite of the more negative states that we experience?

38
00:06:11,516 --> 00:06:16,281
How does hatred transmute into love and cruelty into compassion?

39
00:06:16,903 --> 00:06:21,247
How loneliness transmutes into solitude?

40
00:06:21,867 --> 00:06:22,548
Things like that.

41
00:06:22,649 --> 00:06:28,014
How stinginess and selfishness transmute into generosity?

42
00:06:30,396 --> 00:06:35,802
So the first thing is to recognize how important this quality of equanimity is.

43
00:06:36,964 --> 00:06:41,689
That's what we've been developing when we're practicing this quiet abiding.

44
00:06:43,310 --> 00:06:56,422
The thing about equanimity in this sense is that it's the platform, you see, upon which these other qualities can develop more purely.

45
00:06:57,682 --> 00:06:59,165
It seems to balance them out.

46
00:06:59,524 --> 00:07:05,250
It seems to give them a pure basis to arise from.

47
00:07:05,939 --> 00:07:09,303
And that's really the importance of this quality of equanimity.

48
00:07:10,204 --> 00:07:11,365
What is that quality?

49
00:07:11,425 --> 00:07:17,995
From the mind's point of view, it's coming from a position of don't know or not sure.

50
00:07:18,836 --> 00:07:19,697
So we're open.

51
00:07:20,418 --> 00:07:21,259
We're actually open.

52
00:07:21,300 --> 00:07:23,963
We're ready to receive some information.

53
00:07:25,144 --> 00:07:30,112
And from the heart's point of view, it's not coming from a prejudicial situation.

54
00:07:30,411 --> 00:07:35,658
It's not being discolored by whether you like somebody or don't like somebody.

55
00:07:36,262 --> 00:07:41,170
It's an open-heartedness and an open-mindedness.

56
00:07:41,209 --> 00:07:47,517
That's the qualities of this upeka, equanimity.

57
00:07:48,559 --> 00:07:57,872
And you'll see that some writers, like Jnana Ponika in his book on Vision of the Dhamma, quite clearly states that this is the greatest of all virtues.

58
00:07:59,653 --> 00:08:04,060
Because of that, because it sustains the balance of the others, you see.

59
00:08:05,761 --> 00:08:16,879
So when it comes to something like the other three illimitables, there are four qualities that are called illimitables, love, compassion, joy, and this equanimity.

60
00:08:17,379 --> 00:08:23,029
And they're limitables in the sense that there's no end to which you can develop them.

61
00:08:23,630 --> 00:08:25,033
It's an indefinite development.

62
00:08:25,434 --> 00:08:30,822
We can't say infinite or eternal, but we can definitely say indefinite.

63
00:08:31,697 --> 00:08:57,552
and because there are innumerable numbers of beings in the world there doesn't seem to be an end to the amount of beings that you can offer your good will towards so these three limitables starting with this idea of love you see metta so after this when we do after the walking period we'll do an extended practice of metta and

64
00:08:57,787 --> 00:09:23,440
those are all the qualities that you would expect of a good friend companionship, interest gentleness, openness companionship all the qualities that you would expect of a good friend would be included in the idea of metta

65
00:09:24,279 --> 00:09:36,044
And when it comes to the active qualities, so you've got this passive quality of equanimity and you've got these active qualities of love, compassion and joy.

66
00:09:36,645 --> 00:09:43,520
When it comes to those three active qualities, love again becomes the basis of your relationships.

67
00:09:44,226 --> 00:09:49,315
Now, in later Buddhism, in the Mahayana Buddhism, they stressed compassion a great deal.

68
00:09:50,216 --> 00:10:01,594
And that really was a historical development because it was felt that the early schools had been too self-centered, too much about saving themselves.

69
00:10:01,573 --> 00:10:08,344
And one of the adjustments that was made during that time was to bring in the idea of compassion.

70
00:10:08,625 --> 00:10:20,462
So often if you take refuge with the Mahayana school, you take the vow not to enter into Pandibhānta, everybody else goes in there.

71
00:10:21,904 --> 00:10:26,652
Which wasn't, luckily for us, the Buddha's own decision.

72
00:10:26,672 --> 00:10:27,413
So...

73
00:10:28,625 --> 00:10:43,764
the reason why the Buddha in the original scriptures talks about give the spider a respite probably dropped to his death

74
00:10:47,102 --> 00:11:06,832
So this metta, the Buddha himself, we talk about now his own teachings, that was what he reinforced.

75
00:11:07,572 --> 00:11:14,679
That was one of his teachings and he would balance it really with the Vipassana.

76
00:11:15,461 --> 00:11:29,057
In the discourse on loving-kindness he says that we should develop this open love and it should be balanced with insight meditation.

77
00:11:31,383 --> 00:11:46,244
There's a very good reason for that, because if you only do vipassana, there's a great danger that it remains a sort of heady thing, and it doesn't move.

78
00:11:46,664 --> 00:11:48,368
It doesn't move.

79
00:11:48,408 --> 00:11:52,232
The wisdom can become a sort of indifference.

80
00:11:52,673 --> 00:11:54,557
Have I told you the story of these two monks?

81
00:11:55,136 --> 00:11:56,158
Did I mention that?

82
00:11:56,178 --> 00:11:57,900
Because I always tell these stories.

83
00:11:59,003 --> 00:12:00,445
I never know when I've told it and when I haven't.

84
00:12:02,044 --> 00:12:07,230
Well, a couple of things happened when I was in the East which sort of really showed this up, you see.

85
00:12:07,870 --> 00:12:14,217
Because I was with one monk and there was a cat and it obviously killed this mouse and it was still playing with it.

86
00:12:14,238 --> 00:12:17,721
And I said to this monk, I said, why didn't you stop that?

87
00:12:17,761 --> 00:12:19,583
Because this particular cat was well fed.

88
00:12:20,445 --> 00:12:24,929
He said, well, it's cat karma, it's mouse karma.

89
00:12:27,138 --> 00:12:41,990
And I was at another monastery and there was three or four of us just sitting on this bench talking and this cat suddenly leapt out and jumped on a bird.

90
00:12:42,292 --> 00:12:51,648
And one of the monks, who was fairly elderly, shot up like lightning, got a hold of his cat, gave it one hell of a belt, and then saved this bird.

91
00:12:52,067 --> 00:12:54,331
But unfortunately, the lungs were punctured, it had died.

92
00:12:54,873 --> 00:13:02,004
So he very beautifully held it up by the wings and chanted the sort of death chant, all compounded things arise and pass away.

93
00:13:04,769 --> 00:13:15,248
So what was the difference between the first monk and the cat karma business and the second monk and his jumping up in an attempt to save a bird, you see?

94
00:13:16,431 --> 00:13:24,785
And the difference was that the second monk realized that his consciousness was also part of their awareness, part of their karma.

95
00:13:24,765 --> 00:13:27,850
There wasn't that indifference to suffering.

96
00:13:27,870 --> 00:13:33,039
There wasn't that separation between that knowing, as it were, and what it knew.

97
00:13:33,821 --> 00:13:36,826
So when we're sitting in vipassana, we create this distance.

98
00:13:37,346 --> 00:13:41,975
We have to do so in order to see things more clearly.

99
00:13:42,355 --> 00:13:43,317
And we go into it.

100
00:13:43,577 --> 00:13:49,827
Sometimes, of course, you can lace your looking with a sense of kindness.

101
00:13:50,702 --> 00:13:54,207
I haven't mentioned that over the weekend, but you might find that also softens things.

102
00:13:54,227 --> 00:14:03,539
So, like when you're investigating, say, feelings of depression, you can still investigate them, but you can bring a sense of kindness to your investigation.

103
00:14:03,559 --> 00:14:06,644
And that has quite a softening effect.

104
00:14:06,663 --> 00:14:17,638
So here we have, you see, two incidents where the one, you know, was practicing, or at least had understood that there was no connection to be made.

105
00:14:18,479 --> 00:14:22,466
and the other one found an immediate connection with the suffering of the bird, you see.

106
00:14:24,690 --> 00:14:36,471
I remember a woman came to see me in one of the interviews and said that her partner found her cold and unresponsive after she'd meditated.

107
00:14:37,024 --> 00:14:40,130
So I said to her, well, don't you do any metta after you meditate?

108
00:14:40,991 --> 00:14:41,452
She said, no.

109
00:14:41,594 --> 00:14:42,995
I said, well, you've got to do metta.

110
00:14:43,277 --> 00:14:48,346
And you've got to bring your partner to mind, and often a bit of metta, you see.

111
00:14:49,128 --> 00:14:51,993
And, well, that cleared that one up.

112
00:14:52,013 --> 00:14:55,539
So you have to reconnect, you see.

113
00:14:55,559 --> 00:14:57,342
You have to reconnect with the world.

114
00:14:59,486 --> 00:15:00,349
And...

115
00:15:02,049 --> 00:15:16,370
Once we've developed that reconnection, it's a specific quality, method is a specific quality of having the same relationship with everybody, in fact with all beings, a friendliness with all beings.

116
00:15:16,770 --> 00:15:22,578
So that means it goes beyond this like and dislike, and that's where the attachment is.

117
00:15:22,678 --> 00:15:30,149
The attachment isn't in the friendliness, the attachment is in just this personality thing of like and dislike.

118
00:15:30,282 --> 00:15:32,585
Now, I'm not so sure we can ever get over that.

119
00:15:32,846 --> 00:15:34,567
It's just knowing that it's there.

120
00:15:34,607 --> 00:15:41,758
Even when you read the scriptures, there's definitely for me a feeling that the Buddha had his inner crowd.

121
00:15:42,418 --> 00:15:52,172
Obviously, the earlier disciples who stayed with him, Moggallana, Sariputta, they seem to form a sort of inner group, you know.

122
00:15:52,152 --> 00:16:07,514
And there's a man called Kasapa who actually leads the council after the Buddha dies, who is definitely considered to be an Arahant and worthy of respect and all that sort of stuff.

123
00:16:07,533 --> 00:16:16,826
But there's a feeling that whenever he arrives, everybody goes... And he's one of these hard forest-blowing monks, you know, hard on the Vinaya and all that.

124
00:16:17,802 --> 00:16:21,427
And after the Buddha's death, he meets Ananda.

125
00:16:21,768 --> 00:16:24,311
Ananda was the Buddha's companion for the last 20 years.

126
00:16:24,991 --> 00:16:28,736
And also an awakened being.

127
00:16:29,258 --> 00:16:32,422
And when he meets him, he calls him like a little kid or something.

128
00:16:32,643 --> 00:16:35,886
He talks to him as somebody below him.

129
00:16:36,148 --> 00:16:38,510
And Ananda, who's with Ananda, gets angry with him.

130
00:16:38,490 --> 00:16:49,410
So there's some sort of, even at that level, there's just a natural quality of the way personalities touch each other.

131
00:16:50,052 --> 00:16:56,703
But that shouldn't be a barrier to our way, to the way that we actually treat somebody.

132
00:16:56,884 --> 00:16:57,546
This is the point.

133
00:16:58,724 --> 00:17:06,659
In other words, that you like somebody or dislike them is probably a personality issue, just the way we are.

134
00:17:07,140 --> 00:17:12,048
But that doesn't mean to say that we should therefore treat somebody any the less friendly because of that.

135
00:17:12,710 --> 00:17:18,480
And it's making that distinction which creates this quality of universal love, you see.

136
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:19,482
And that's the metaphor.

137
00:17:24,846 --> 00:17:40,152
Now, the reason why I say that method is the basic relationship that we have with each other, with all beings, is because you can see that once you're a friend to somebody, the other two illimitables arise quite naturally.

138
00:17:40,952 --> 00:17:47,282
So if a friend falls ill or into misfortune, there's a natural desire to help.

139
00:17:47,303 --> 00:17:50,929
It's not a problem, it just arises naturally out of that friendliness.

140
00:17:50,949 --> 00:17:51,951
You don't have to work on it.

141
00:17:53,467 --> 00:18:00,334
And if somebody, if a friend has good fortune, you tend to congratulate them and you're happy for them.

142
00:18:00,413 --> 00:18:05,960
You feel there's a resonance, a resonance, a joyful resonance.

143
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:09,403
It's called sympathetic joy or reciprocal joy.

144
00:18:10,085 --> 00:18:11,145
It's a resonance.

145
00:18:11,365 --> 00:18:13,288
You feel their happiness and you're happy for them.

146
00:18:14,229 --> 00:18:16,230
If they win the lottery, you're extremely happy.

147
00:18:16,411 --> 00:18:17,172
You don't want a penny.

148
00:18:19,954 --> 00:18:21,836
You're not upset when they don't even buy you a drink.

149
00:18:23,048 --> 00:18:29,182
See, it's that sort of, and you're still gleeful that they're having such a good life.

150
00:18:31,226 --> 00:18:42,069
So that love, you see, that Buddha asked us to develop is the platform for all these other qualities.

151
00:18:45,644 --> 00:18:53,633
Now, when it comes to love itself, as we've pointed out, the big obstacle there is affection.

152
00:18:53,794 --> 00:18:54,954
The obvious one is hatred.

153
00:18:55,015 --> 00:18:56,236
I mean, that's pretty straightforward.

154
00:18:56,936 --> 00:19:01,301
But the more subtle one is affection or attachment.

155
00:19:02,324 --> 00:19:07,769
And you can see this often in the case of a parent.

156
00:19:10,686 --> 00:19:16,932
You know, like if their little child comes home with a black eye, you know, it's the end of the world, you know.

157
00:19:16,952 --> 00:19:21,269
But if it's a cheeky kid from down the street, well, it deserves it.

158
00:19:22,583 --> 00:19:33,173
There's that sort of attachment which sort of creates a speciality around the person whom you have that relationship with.

159
00:19:34,134 --> 00:19:37,798
Now, as I say, you can't do anything about that.

160
00:19:37,858 --> 00:19:41,923
It's just like when we open up to ourselves and we find these various states.

161
00:19:42,443 --> 00:19:50,633
It's a case of making ourselves aware of that and making sure that we're making decisions, intentions that go the other way.

162
00:19:50,613 --> 00:20:05,904
Now one of the things this weekend was really trying to catch these intentions a bit because remember it's at the point of intention that we have this ability to choose and we can see the quality of that intention.

163
00:20:06,019 --> 00:20:21,599
And if you see that the intention you're making is flavored or is laced with some sort of attachment, then just make sure you make the right intention and work from that intention.

164
00:20:22,401 --> 00:20:24,363
So it's just like with food, you see.

165
00:20:24,884 --> 00:20:31,352
With food, as soon as we make the intention to eat to nourish the body, it creates a different relationship to food.

166
00:20:31,923 --> 00:20:35,146
But as soon as you seek their happiness, then that's it.

167
00:20:35,527 --> 00:20:37,548
It doesn't mean that the food doesn't make you happy.

168
00:20:37,648 --> 00:20:42,433
It's just that your intention corrupts your relationship to food.

169
00:20:42,454 --> 00:20:49,721
It then becomes, you know, sort of a dependency.

170
00:20:50,423 --> 00:20:54,807
Your happiness becomes dependent on a particular food that you like.

171
00:20:58,686 --> 00:21:07,182
When it comes to compassion, that again is, I mean the opposite is obvious, cruelty.

172
00:21:07,383 --> 00:21:08,766
We don't have to work too much on that.

173
00:21:10,308 --> 00:21:17,521
But the subtle one is grief, you see, pity, pity, grief.

174
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:28,107
That's a bit difficult for us to grasp really, because the association of compassion with grief is quite intimate.

175
00:21:28,868 --> 00:21:36,599
We think that the more we feel sorry for somebody, the more in a sense we're compassionate.

176
00:21:37,500 --> 00:21:47,234
But if you think about it, to move from the heart of compassion is actually a joyful moment.

177
00:21:47,255 --> 00:21:49,617
A heart is filled with joy when you're helping somebody.

178
00:21:52,432 --> 00:22:08,756
Let's take a very simple case, if a blind man wants to walk across the street, and you just do it out of kindness, and you take his arm and lead him across.

179
00:22:10,377 --> 00:22:11,941
A sense of joy, isn't it?

180
00:22:14,785 --> 00:22:19,411
If you grieve for the blind person, then what is it you're adding to that?

181
00:22:20,231 --> 00:22:22,035
And is it necessary?

182
00:22:33,945 --> 00:22:38,411
Sometimes it's easier to understand that when you actually think about yourself.

183
00:22:39,211 --> 00:22:48,201
Supposing you were, shall we say, struck down or something, and everybody around you started weeping and wailing.

184
00:22:49,061 --> 00:22:49,923
I mean, would that help you?

185
00:22:49,962 --> 00:22:55,448
It's like it just makes you more sad, you know, go away.

186
00:22:55,488 --> 00:22:58,131
I've got enough grief.

187
00:23:00,727 --> 00:23:05,473
If you take, for instance, which is, you see, these things are completely understandable.

188
00:23:05,855 --> 00:23:13,788
And I think you have to make a distinction here between good and bad in the sense of evil and skillful, unskillful, wholesome, unwholesome.

189
00:23:13,807 --> 00:23:16,352
We're not saying that grief is some sort of great evil.

190
00:23:16,972 --> 00:23:19,596
We're just saying it's unnecessary suffering.

191
00:23:20,698 --> 00:23:22,461
It's not necessary.

192
00:23:22,500 --> 00:23:27,409
We can relieve ourselves of the need to grieve for somebody else.

193
00:23:30,005 --> 00:23:32,508
it undermines the purity of our compassion.

194
00:23:35,250 --> 00:23:57,176
If you take for instance somebody who's feeling ill and they go to the doctor and they have a diagnosis and the doctor tells them that they've only got six weeks to live but they just can't contain their grief and they're blubbering and saying, how would you feel about that?

195
00:23:57,156 --> 00:23:59,819
You think, this is highly unprofessional.

196
00:24:03,744 --> 00:24:09,290
So, of certain professionals, we're quite happy for them to tell us, you know, in a kind, sympathetic way.

197
00:24:09,310 --> 00:24:16,759
We're not asking them to be brutal, in a kind, sympathetic way, in an understanding way, but we would hate for them to collapse into tears.

198
00:24:16,819 --> 00:24:19,982
As a surgeon, as he's sort of doing his job, he's weeping.

199
00:24:20,042 --> 00:24:23,166
I mean, it wouldn't help, would it?

200
00:24:23,186 --> 00:24:26,691
It means there's something definitely wrong, you know?

201
00:24:27,817 --> 00:24:41,494
So, if you really look into pity, pity, you know, that sort of, perhaps pity is a slightly better word, although it melds easily into grief.

202
00:24:42,435 --> 00:24:48,503
You see, if you like going back a little bit to love, when somebody dies, you're left with grief, okay?

203
00:24:49,384 --> 00:24:50,465
Now, what is that grief?

204
00:24:50,486 --> 00:24:53,109
Is that a measure of your love or a measure of your attachment?

205
00:24:53,369 --> 00:24:54,230
That's the point.

206
00:24:54,835 --> 00:25:00,801
You know, I had an old lady come to me whose son had died, and she'd been grieving over this son for years.

207
00:25:01,803 --> 00:25:03,345
And it just wouldn't leave her.

208
00:25:03,365 --> 00:25:04,665
It just depressed her all the time.

209
00:25:05,366 --> 00:25:15,577
And when we discussed it, and she came to realize that actually the grief was a measure of her attachment and not her love, you know, it just lifted.

210
00:25:15,597 --> 00:25:19,762
I could see it was lifting even then and there when I was talking to her.

211
00:25:19,742 --> 00:25:47,606
she actually wrote me a letter later saying that all her grief had gone once she'd separated the idea of grief from love so remember that an attachment is like that word is a rather nice word it's like you're glued and when somebody you're glued to is sort of ripped out of your life in death you're just left with this wound you're left with an inner wound you know

212
00:25:47,923 --> 00:25:56,556
And just because you might now think, well, this is because of my attachment, it doesn't mean to say that therefore it hasn't to be suffered and allowed to heal.

213
00:25:56,797 --> 00:25:58,179
And that's the grieving process.

214
00:25:58,839 --> 00:26:09,654
But as soon as you say to yourself, well, this grief is a measure of my love, every time your grieving begins to lessen, you have to say to yourself, well, I don't love that person as much as I did.

215
00:26:09,694 --> 00:26:10,636
So you've got to grieve again.

216
00:26:11,137 --> 00:26:12,298
You've got to keep pumping it up.

217
00:26:13,661 --> 00:26:16,345
Because you can't handle the guilt of not loving the person.

218
00:26:18,011 --> 00:26:19,596
But love is easy, isn't it?

219
00:26:19,695 --> 00:26:23,324
Love is easy with things.

220
00:26:23,443 --> 00:26:25,328
It allows people their destiny.

221
00:26:26,170 --> 00:26:30,519
If a person has had to die young or whatever, that's it.

222
00:26:30,559 --> 00:26:31,883
You let them go.

223
00:26:31,903 --> 00:26:36,173
It's just the way it is, as we say.

224
00:26:38,701 --> 00:26:45,167
So now this compassion, one of its things is grief.

225
00:26:45,528 --> 00:26:53,538
But there's an even more subtle problem, especially with compassion, and that is that it's the do-good factor.

226
00:26:53,577 --> 00:27:00,285
It makes you feel good when you do good, especially somebody who thanks you and obviously appreciates your help.

227
00:27:01,406 --> 00:27:06,092
And then there's a very subtle shift, often without a person knowing it,

228
00:27:06,730 --> 00:27:10,366
that in fact you start doing good in order to feel good.

229
00:27:11,551 --> 00:27:14,022
And then you become the classic do-gooder.

230
00:27:15,269 --> 00:27:22,779
and the do-gooder is the person who's going to do you the good they want to do you, whether you like it or not.

231
00:27:23,259 --> 00:27:41,866
And you can always catch that little do-gooder in ourselves, because if you've jumped the gun, you see, and this is where this equanimity comes, because with equanimity, one goes to the person who needs help with that open-minded, open-heartedness, and you say, what do you want?

232
00:27:42,353 --> 00:27:48,332
And then when they tell you what they want, then you can say to yourself, well, can I do it or can't I do it?

233
00:27:48,712 --> 00:27:50,057
It's a very simple choice.

234
00:27:50,117 --> 00:27:51,080
If you can, then you help.

235
00:27:51,121 --> 00:27:52,464
If you can't, you can't.

236
00:27:52,883 --> 00:28:08,069
But if you jump the gun and suggest to them what they need and they brush you off and you feel hurt, then you know there's something else going on in this transaction.

237
00:28:10,032 --> 00:28:12,277
So it's pretty good.

238
00:28:12,457 --> 00:28:13,980
You have to be careful with that one.

239
00:28:18,549 --> 00:28:29,323
The other thing about compassion that I think people feel these days is a feeling of impotency, a feeling of not being able to do what they know has to be done.

240
00:28:31,865 --> 00:28:45,823
Even about things which are big, like this disaster in Burma or in China, or the fact that we now have got a food shortage for no reason, but it seems, of the futures market.

241
00:28:46,596 --> 00:29:01,701
people get into that emotional involvement with the world and what's happening to the world, and then they get this terrible feeling of frustration, complete impotency, feel unable to do anything, unable to do enough.

242
00:29:02,644 --> 00:29:07,932
And that really is not, again, a pure compassion.

243
00:29:07,951 --> 00:29:09,515
That's not coming from equanimity.

244
00:29:09,674 --> 00:29:11,337
That's coming, again, from pride.

245
00:29:12,095 --> 00:29:17,060
And pride here doesn't know the limits of power and influence.

246
00:29:17,721 --> 00:29:22,067
So when we do something, it's within our power.

247
00:29:22,086 --> 00:29:26,272
You have a ring of power around you, what you can actually do.

248
00:29:27,094 --> 00:29:31,138
And then there's another outer ring of influence, what you can get other people to do.

249
00:29:31,839 --> 00:29:33,781
And then beyond that, that's it.

250
00:29:34,048 --> 00:29:37,034
That's the end of what you can do and can get others to do.

251
00:29:37,074 --> 00:29:43,324
And it's just being able to accept that and being equanimous with it, that one has done what one can do.

252
00:29:44,384 --> 00:29:46,769
I went on a retreat once.

253
00:29:48,111 --> 00:29:52,817
There were four different traditions.

254
00:29:52,837 --> 00:29:53,880
No, no, there's...

255
00:29:53,859 --> 00:29:55,563
There was a Chan teacher.

256
00:29:56,144 --> 00:29:57,486
There was me doing the old vipassana.

257
00:29:58,307 --> 00:30:02,212
There was an Orthodox monk.

258
00:30:02,232 --> 00:30:05,397
And there was, would you believe it, the Archbishop of Canterbury himself.

259
00:30:07,500 --> 00:30:11,446
And we were supposed to be sharing these teachings.

260
00:30:13,351 --> 00:30:20,103
And on the koan, he gave us all these koans to do, you see, and some of them, of course, just don't make sense to me at all.

261
00:30:20,763 --> 00:30:32,765
But the last few at the end were very modern koans, and one of them was, which really struck me, you see, it said, what can you do when you've done everything you can do?

262
00:30:34,307 --> 00:30:37,653
What can you do when you've done everything you can do?

263
00:30:38,578 --> 00:30:43,327
And it's that point where we think we can always do more than we can.

264
00:30:44,509 --> 00:30:46,192
And that's where the frustration comes.

265
00:30:46,252 --> 00:30:49,720
That's where the sense of impotency can come.

266
00:30:50,381 --> 00:30:52,124
So we also have to be careful of that.

267
00:30:52,404 --> 00:30:58,596
We have to be sort of realistic about what our role is in any given situation.

268
00:30:59,977 --> 00:31:19,856
You know, even when it comes to, say, giving to charities, you know, they're constantly coming to the door, these, you know, and it always says 50p, you know, or, you know, 50 cents, and you think, well, by the end, by the end of it, you're giving 50 cents to all these charities, you end up being a pauper.

269
00:31:19,876 --> 00:31:21,359
So it's a case of...

270
00:31:21,339 --> 00:31:27,817
sort of recognizing that, well, this is what I can do, this is what I can get other people to do, and then you just rest in that.

271
00:31:28,137 --> 00:31:30,163
And that's the quality of equanimity, you see.

272
00:31:30,884 --> 00:31:32,228
That's the quality of equanimity.

273
00:31:36,815 --> 00:31:52,410
So sympathetic joy, I mean that's a lovely quality isn't it, to be able to rejoice in other people's good fortune and it undermines the sort of obvious thing which is envy isn't it and jealousy.

274
00:31:53,250 --> 00:31:56,996
And those are two things that we don't like to see in ourselves.

275
00:31:57,457 --> 00:31:58,238
Envy is not so bad.

276
00:31:58,258 --> 00:32:03,486
You can sort of say to somebody, I envy your lifestyle or something.

277
00:32:04,126 --> 00:32:16,845
But jealousy is one of these traits within us which we don't particularly like to see because when we're jealous, we're actually saying to myself, well, this person is better than me.

278
00:32:18,309 --> 00:32:24,279
So it's often a very subconscious thing which comes out in all sorts of ways.

279
00:32:26,103 --> 00:32:34,857
And in our meditation, you know, if it comes up in meditation, very quickly sort of, you know, really catch it and get the feel of it.

280
00:32:34,877 --> 00:32:38,022
It's not a pleasant mental state at all.

281
00:32:39,943 --> 00:32:46,369
You know, there would have been a time when I would have gone around saying, well, I'm not jealous of anybody, you know.

282
00:32:47,029 --> 00:32:56,959
But I remember, this is a little while back, I used to try to write plays at one point.

283
00:32:58,140 --> 00:33:06,968
And by this time, I was beginning to recognize that I wasn't quite going to make Shakespearean standards.

284
00:33:07,008 --> 00:33:09,630
But there was this young fellow who got a play on, you see.

285
00:33:09,609 --> 00:33:14,135
And one of the few times I really caught my jealousy.

286
00:33:15,057 --> 00:33:17,279
It was a really sort of nasty moment.

287
00:33:17,359 --> 00:33:18,301
I thought, oh my God!

288
00:33:22,027 --> 00:33:26,071
And it really is a sort of a nasty sort of emotion.

289
00:33:26,092 --> 00:33:30,458
But it really undermines joy, you see.

290
00:33:30,518 --> 00:33:33,040
This is the problem with all these negative things.

291
00:33:33,162 --> 00:33:35,044
They kill your own joy.

292
00:33:35,159 --> 00:33:38,742
You can't be joyful and jealous and envious at the same time.

293
00:33:39,403 --> 00:33:42,968
This is one of the problems.

294
00:33:44,249 --> 00:33:57,243
The more subtle energy, the more subtle thing about joy is of course sort of overdoing it, getting excited, jumping up and down a bit too much, you know, so that it takes on a sort of false character.

295
00:33:57,663 --> 00:33:59,226
You have to be careful of that too.

296
00:34:00,067 --> 00:34:08,726
But it's probably the easiest one for us to enjoy more purely anyway, especially with friends.

297
00:34:09,414 --> 00:34:28,505
But going back now to this fundamental position of love, you see, this metta, this goodwill, it's translated sometimes in a slightly mawkish way as loving-kindness, which they take, I think, from a 14th century mystic.

298
00:34:29,387 --> 00:34:36,097
But to me it just means goodwill, which I think translates it very openly.

299
00:34:37,934 --> 00:34:51,824
And then all the other things that we suffer from, you see, trying to find a way to generate the opposite.

300
00:34:52,447 --> 00:35:21,862
and you'll see this evening that whereas in Vipassana we try to stop the thinking mind try to stop the imaginative mind completely it's a hindrance to actually seeing things as they really are when it comes to developing these qualities within us we actually begin to use the imaginative mind to reinforce and to develop certain qualities so when we practice the metta as we did a little bit last night

301
00:35:22,449 --> 00:35:27,824
You bring people to mind, you see, and you offer them your goodwill, your blessings.

302
00:35:29,086 --> 00:35:35,682
Whether these things actually affect them or not is up to you, whether you want to believe that or not.

303
00:35:35,923 --> 00:35:39,092
But what it's doing is developing an attitude within us.

304
00:35:40,117 --> 00:35:50,891
And as we widen that scope out to include all beings, we're just slowly developing an attitude of goodwill to all beings.

305
00:35:51,572 --> 00:35:57,260
And we're using these very faculties that in the past have become hindrance.

306
00:35:58,282 --> 00:36:00,945
And it's the same with the compassion and the joy.

307
00:36:05,161 --> 00:36:12,985
Now if you look at just other things like loneliness, sometimes you might feel lonely.

308
00:36:14,429 --> 00:36:17,500
What do people do when they feel lonely?

309
00:36:18,998 --> 00:36:24,463
And normally, you know, you'd ring up a friend and say, I'm so, you know, I'm lonely tonight.

310
00:36:24,804 --> 00:36:25,445
I'm lonely too.

311
00:36:26,547 --> 00:36:29,170
Two lonely people watching a film or something.

312
00:36:29,891 --> 00:36:37,480
And it's that sense of, now, to feel the loneliness, to feel the loneliness, what is it?

313
00:36:37,619 --> 00:36:39,461
What is the feeling of it?

314
00:36:39,481 --> 00:36:42,806
So this is how you begin, you see, just like in your meditation.

315
00:36:43,286 --> 00:36:48,532
You begin by sinking into that, the feel of loneliness.

316
00:36:48,512 --> 00:36:51,478
And it's a lack of self-love, isn't it?

317
00:36:51,719 --> 00:36:53,061
That's basically what it is.

318
00:36:53,342 --> 00:36:54,445
You don't like being on your own.

319
00:36:56,528 --> 00:37:02,900
And as you sink in there, you see, you might get all sorts of things, sort of little blips arriving.

320
00:37:02,920 --> 00:37:04,003
You know, you're unlovable.

321
00:37:04,063 --> 00:37:05,525
Nobody loves you anymore.

322
00:37:05,505 --> 00:37:08,713
All that sort of rubbish comes up, you know.

323
00:37:09,074 --> 00:37:21,000
But if you stay with your vipassana and you go into the feeling base of it, you see, and as it begins to evaporate, you see, then the opposite begins to appear.

324
00:37:20,980 --> 00:37:25,005
So when loneliness disappears, what can you expect at the end of the line, you see?

325
00:37:26,005 --> 00:37:27,186
So it's solitude, isn't it?

326
00:37:28,027 --> 00:37:31,731
And solitude is being perfectly at peace and at one with yourself.

327
00:37:33,474 --> 00:37:40,922
So to develop that, you have to give blessings to yourself.

328
00:37:40,963 --> 00:37:45,148
You have to start turning this metta and this compassion towards yourself.

329
00:37:46,630 --> 00:37:54,447
And that's how you begin to undermine these feelings of depression, loneliness, lack of self-esteem.

330
00:37:55,068 --> 00:38:04,061
So you actually, you don't get caught up in the usual fantasies and the thinking around those negative feelings.

331
00:38:04,081 --> 00:38:05,164
You do your vipassana.

332
00:38:05,364 --> 00:38:10,932
Anyway, you'll be on a bus, you could be standing under a tree, doesn't matter, and you just sink into that feeling.

333
00:38:11,353 --> 00:38:21,750
And then as it begins to loosen up, you don't have to wait for it to completely end, best if you can, but not necessary, then you start offering yourself these blessings.

334
00:38:23,822 --> 00:38:27,086
And in that way you're developing another conditioning.

335
00:38:28,829 --> 00:38:33,994
Remember a lot of our opinions about ourselves we've picked up from other people.

336
00:38:34,775 --> 00:38:40,983
You know, it's when teachers have told us we're stupid or our parents have told us, you know, they'd rather keep a rat.

337
00:38:43,726 --> 00:38:44,387
Things like that.

338
00:38:44,688 --> 00:38:51,635
And we sort of pick this up from people and ingested it and it's become part of our own mentality.

339
00:38:51,699 --> 00:38:54,923
And it's a case of, you don't get into blaming them, by the way.

340
00:38:55,344 --> 00:38:59,550
That's just something that naturally happens to us as children.

341
00:39:00,150 --> 00:39:02,034
And it's just recognizing that, you know.

342
00:39:02,675 --> 00:39:14,329
But again, always not to get caught up in the fantasies, in the way we talk to ourselves.

343
00:39:14,931 --> 00:39:20,137
So that gives you some sort of hints as to how we can, you know, generate...

344
00:39:20,842 --> 00:39:40,842
the positive side there are many other qualities and the final one I'd like to mention is the one that the Buddha always began his talks with whenever he talked to lay people whenever he introduced himself as a teacher and what his teaching was about he always talked first of all about generosity

345
00:39:40,974 --> 00:39:47,304
And then the nature of good conduct, wholesome, ethical conduct.

346
00:39:47,324 --> 00:39:51,451
Then he would talk about the heavens and future life births and all that.

347
00:39:51,731 --> 00:39:56,918
And then when he felt that the audience was malleable, ready for the thing, he'd smack them with the old dukkha.

348
00:39:58,440 --> 00:40:00,164
The Four Noble Truths.

349
00:40:00,184 --> 00:40:02,206
There is suffering.

350
00:40:02,677 --> 00:40:07,802
but he sort of softened them up first with a couple of nice things.

351
00:40:08,643 --> 00:40:18,617
And generosity is, you might say, a very, from the Buddha's point of view, a really sort of important quality to develop.

352
00:40:19,438 --> 00:40:25,224
And when you're generous,

353
00:40:25,458 --> 00:40:26,619
It's an act of love, yeah?

354
00:40:26,639 --> 00:40:27,601
It's an act of compassion.

355
00:40:27,641 --> 00:40:30,789
You're giving something for the benefit of somebody else.

356
00:40:30,809 --> 00:40:35,036
But in doing so, you have to give something up.

357
00:40:35,056 --> 00:40:38,143
You either have to give up some of your wealth or some of your time.

358
00:40:38,804 --> 00:40:41,610
And to do that means an act of renunciation.

359
00:40:41,927 --> 00:40:54,144
And when that renunciation, every time we give an act of renunciation, we actually are cutting into the solidity of the self.

360
00:40:54,164 --> 00:40:56,547
So where does somebody might say, can you come and help me?

361
00:40:56,568 --> 00:40:59,813
And you want to watch your favorite program on TV.

362
00:41:00,614 --> 00:41:01,876
You have to give that up.

363
00:41:02,777 --> 00:41:05,099
And that's the attachment to this program.

364
00:41:06,181 --> 00:41:06,282
Okay.

365
00:41:07,882 --> 00:41:15,670
Every time you make an offering of your wealth, you're giving up something which you could have bought for yourself, which you could have enjoyed for yourself.

366
00:41:16,793 --> 00:41:33,012
And every time you do that, especially in an act of generosity, which, shall we say, just tweaks a bit, you don't have to really suffer, but where you know you're actually giving something up, then that's undercutting this attachment to yourself.

367
00:41:34,864 --> 00:41:42,175
This idea to the concreteness of the self, just being able to let go of something for the benefit of the other.

368
00:41:47,807 --> 00:42:06,777
and when you give whether you give to a charity or to a friend or whatever again it's always getting this intention right being very clear about your intention so that at the point of saying yes or the point of giving something

369
00:42:06,757 --> 00:42:15,110
Your intention is very clear that you're giving this for the benefit of the other and you do not want any return.

370
00:42:15,630 --> 00:42:18,315
It's a complete letting go of the gift, whatever it might be.

371
00:42:20,137 --> 00:42:24,083
So if your friend says, you know, can you come and help me do a bit of decoration?

372
00:42:25,766 --> 00:42:30,353
When you ask them, could they come and do a bit of decoration, they say no, that's fine.

373
00:42:31,344 --> 00:42:33,969
There's no pain, no sorrow.

374
00:42:33,989 --> 00:42:37,695
You've completely forgotten, in fact, that you'd help them do their decoration.

375
00:42:37,795 --> 00:42:40,579
It's that sort of giving.

376
00:42:41,059 --> 00:42:44,885
Now, if you've got to put that clearly in your mind, just like food, you see?

377
00:42:45,226 --> 00:42:47,369
You say to yourself, this is just to nourish the body.

378
00:42:48,471 --> 00:42:54,219
And then you do the act, or you give your donation or whatever.

379
00:42:54,900 --> 00:42:57,184
Now, as soon as you've done that, of course...

380
00:42:57,164 --> 00:42:59,199
You're bound to get these little comments.

381
00:42:59,844 --> 00:43:02,364
You are such a generous person.

382
00:43:02,750 --> 00:43:08,400
You really are, you're really wonderful, amazing how wonderful you are.

383
00:43:08,420 --> 00:43:10,282
Or, too much, take a bit back.

384
00:43:12,005 --> 00:43:14,469
You can't spend a whole day doing that.

385
00:43:15,512 --> 00:43:18,157
But you know them, you say, ah, that's old Mara.

386
00:43:18,496 --> 00:43:21,663
You've caught her, you've beaten old Mara there.

387
00:43:21,682 --> 00:43:27,592
And very slowly, those voices, those little negative conditionings,

388
00:43:27,572 --> 00:43:34,001
they sort of die away and this more spontaneous action comes.

389
00:43:34,583 --> 00:43:35,764
And that's what we want, isn't it?

390
00:43:35,824 --> 00:43:43,695
We want to live spontaneously, not by way of just some reaction, some old habit, you see.

391
00:43:44,036 --> 00:43:45,557
And that's what the qualities give us.

392
00:43:45,617 --> 00:43:55,572
They give us this feeling of spontaneity in our lives where joy just arises naturally out of any action that we do, you see.

393
00:43:55,552 --> 00:43:59,556
And that's one of the gifts of developing these particular qualities.

394
00:44:16,952 --> 00:44:21,677
So you can see here, can't you, the development of the spiritual life, you know.

395
00:44:21,994 --> 00:44:28,045
The vipassana, the right understanding, getting things right, turning it into intentions.

396
00:44:28,806 --> 00:44:31,512
There's the Eightfold Path, right intention, right attitude.

397
00:44:31,972 --> 00:44:36,822
Turning them into clear intentions, clear intentions.

398
00:44:36,842 --> 00:44:41,369
And then the way we speak, the way we act, even our livelihood.

399
00:44:42,244 --> 00:44:50,639
So how do we turn our livelihood, what we actually do within society, how do we turn that into a spiritual practice?

400
00:44:51,201 --> 00:44:54,126
And again it's turning it into a service.

401
00:44:54,146 --> 00:44:56,170
Again it's that generosity, it's the offering.

402
00:45:00,737 --> 00:45:05,045
And then that whole spiritual practice becomes systemic.

403
00:45:05,161 --> 00:45:08,983
there's not a part of you which is not involved in that progress.

404
00:45:10,364 --> 00:45:15,929
If you stop at any point, there'll be a block, there'll be something, something won't pass, something won't happen for you.

405
00:45:17,452 --> 00:45:21,315
It just has to be like that.

406
00:45:21,335 --> 00:45:34,206
And the last three of the Eightfold Path, the right effort and the right mindfulness and the right concentration, those follow us wherever we go, see?

407
00:45:34,793 --> 00:45:41,242
That's this business of just being in the moment, relaxing into the present moment, wide awake.

408
00:45:43,847 --> 00:45:45,228
That's your default position.

409
00:45:46,231 --> 00:45:47,652
And you can do that all the time.

410
00:45:47,693 --> 00:45:50,177
You don't have to do it just when you're on retreat.

411
00:45:50,197 --> 00:45:56,907
Anytime during the day when there's a break, when you're not doing something, you remind yourself just to fall into that state.

412
00:45:57,748 --> 00:45:58,530
It doesn't matter how long.

413
00:45:58,550 --> 00:45:59,291
It could be a second.

414
00:45:59,670 --> 00:46:00,733
It could be just a second.

415
00:46:02,197 --> 00:46:06,342
And always in that state you can see the next intention.

416
00:46:06,543 --> 00:46:09,226
That's the importance of it.

417
00:46:09,246 --> 00:46:15,211
When you're in a rush, when you're always moving, you get grasped by old conditionings.

418
00:46:16,454 --> 00:46:26,485
But if you can keep collapsing everything into this state of just being here, you can see the next intention.

419
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:30,204
And it gives you that sense of control, you see, over your life.

420
00:46:30,505 --> 00:46:32,590
You're actually guiding yourself.

421
00:46:32,650 --> 00:46:39,043
You're actually moving the way you want to move.

422
00:46:39,063 --> 00:46:42,731
So I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance.

423
00:46:43,373 --> 00:46:47,983
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

424
00:46:52,806 --> 00:47:21,159
you have to say sadhu I feel really bad there were talks that the Buddha gave where the monks did not respond I don't know how he felt there were others when they were the monks were delighted and the listeners were delighted and there were other discourses where the listeners were delighted they always said things that they didn't want to hear

425
00:47:22,168 --> 00:47:27,135
So if we do some walking meditation until about half past seven.

426
00:47:30,059 --> 00:47:41,172
And during this one, in order to support the metta, the better practice, do more just relaxing, just being with the walking.

427
00:47:41,233 --> 00:47:43,074
Don't worry too much about the investigation.

428
00:47:43,315 --> 00:47:45,577
Just develop that quality of calmness.

429
00:47:46,873 --> 00:47:53,784
And just that momentary attention, just momentary attention to what you're doing.

430
00:47:53,804 --> 00:47:56,496
And then we'll come back and do the next one.

